<a href="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/Sport/Article&sz=300x250&c=961768142&t=artid%3d7749c59d-0a4e-4ace-887a-8dac0b82f623%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" target="_blank"><img src="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/Sport/Article&sz=300x250&c=961768142&t=artid%3d7749c59d-0a4e-4ace-887a-8dac0b82f623%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" border="0" alt=""></a>Mbane was Celtic Ladies’ key player in defence and helped to ensure that they conceded only one goal in four matches. In their opening game, where they defeated Gauteng champions Mamelodi Sundowns Ladies 3-0, Mbane proved more than capable of containing the deadly duo of Chantelle Esau and Andisiwe Mgcoyi, who led the attack. Celtic conceded their only goal when they brushed aside Kanatla Ladies 3-1, before thumping Thunderbirds 4-0 to book their final spot.Banyana Banyana coach Desiree Ellis has been at the championships since day one, monitoring players ahead of a busy 2018 schedule for her team. Banyana start the year with back-to-back friendlies against Sweden in Cape Town on 17 and 21 January.Mbane’s incredible performance could be her ticket into Ellis squad.Said the player: “From the first game the pressure was on us to defend the title. “We had to be disciplined and work as a team to achieve this goal. I hope the awards will serve as inspiration for other players who look up to me.”Celtic coach Edwin Lesene has set his sights on matching Palace Super Falcons Ladies’ record of three tournament crowns in a row.“I’m so happy for the girls. They stuck to my game plan to win. They are still young – most of them will return next year,” said Lesene.Celtic Ladies have been a presence in the national champs since 2009.
